## Task tracking

This repo uses `todo-sqlite-cli` for TODOs. The DB path is resolved via the
`.todo-sqlite-cli` marker at the repo root (or `$TODO_SQLITE_CLI_DB`, or the
`--db` flag ‚Äî in that precedence order).

**Before planning or coding, ask the DB ‚Äî do not read a PLAN.md file:**

- `todo-sqlite-cli next` ‚Äî the single task to work on right now. Returns
  the oldest in-progress task, then the oldest partial (paused) task, then
  the highest-priority unblocked pending task. Prefer this over `list` ‚Äî
  it returns one task in one query. When no work remains, `next` prints
  nothing (or `null` under `--json`) and exits 0 ‚Äî use that as a clean
  termination signal.
- `todo-sqlite-cli list` ‚Äî active tasks (in-progress + partial + pending),
  ordered by status then priority. Tabular output is already terse.
- `todo-sqlite-cli list --status partial` (or `pending` / `done` / `all`)
  ‚Äî filter to one status when scanning a subset.
- `todo-sqlite-cli show <id>` ‚Äî details for one task. Default output omits
  default-valued fields (`pending`, `P3`); pass `--verbose` for everything.

**Cheap re-polling (token-frugal):**

- `todo-sqlite-cli list --ids-only` ‚Äî just IDs, one per line. Cheapest way
  to detect change between turns. Combine with `--json` for an ID array.
- `todo-sqlite-cli list --since 2026-05-07` ‚Äî only tasks created on/after a
  date, for incremental updates.
- `todo-sqlite-cli export-todo --format markdown` ‚Äî terse markdown by
  default; pass `--verbose` only when you need every field.
- `todo-sqlite-cli export-completed` ‚Äî compact JSON by default; pass
  `--pretty` only for human review.

**When picking up work:**

- `todo-sqlite-cli start <id>` before coding. If another task was already
  in-progress, it is automatically moved to `partial` (paused, with its
  `started_at` preserved). Pass `--force` to keep multiple tasks
  in-progress simultaneously.
- `todo-sqlite-cli stop <id>` to pause without committing ‚Äî the task moves
  to `partial`, ready to be resumed via `start <id>`.
- `todo-sqlite-cli revert <id>` to discard the start: clears `started_at`
  and returns the task to `pending`.
- `todo-sqlite-cli done <id>` when the change is committed. Idempotent ‚Äî
  safe to call twice.

**When a new task surfaces:**

- `todo-sqlite-cli add "title" --details "..." --tag <area> --priority <P>`
  where `<P>` is `1`-`5` or `P1`-`P5` (priority 1 is highest, 3 is default).
- `--depends-on <id>` on `add` to link a prerequisite at creation time.
  Tasks with unmet dependencies are skipped by `next` and flagged
  `[blocked]` in `list`. Prefer wiring deps at `add` time over editing
  later.

**Editing or annotating a task:**

- `todo-sqlite-cli edit <id> --append-details "note"` ‚Äî appends a progress
  note to existing details with a newline separator. Use this for
  incremental status notes mid-task instead of `--details` (which
  replaces) so prior context isn't lost.
- `todo-sqlite-cli edit <id> --details "new body"` replaces details
  wholesale; `--clear-details` empties them. These three flags are
  mutually exclusive.
- `todo-sqlite-cli edit <id> --add-tag <t>` / `--rm-tag <t>` ‚Äî manage tags
  (repeatable).
- `todo-sqlite-cli edit <id> --add-dep <other-id>` / `--rm-dep <id>` ‚Äî
  manage dependency edges (repeatable; cycles are rejected).
- `todo-sqlite-cli edit <id> --title "..."` / `--priority P2` ‚Äî rename or
  reprioritize.

**Statuses:** `pending` ‚Üí `in-progress` ‚Üí `done`. `partial` is the paused
state for a task that was started and then displaced (or stopped) ‚Äî use
`start` to resume it, `revert` to discard the start.

**Exit codes:** 0 success, 1 user error, 2 system error. Every command
supports `--json` and `--db PATH`.
